description:
Common Sow Thistle (Sonchus oleraceus), which I found at Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve.  This plant resembles the wild lettuces (genus Lactuca), to which it is closely related; however, the leaves are a giveaway that it is something else.  The very long, winged petioles on the larger leaves, the clasping nature of the younger leaves and the fairly variable leaf shape are distinctive for ths species.  None of the wild lettuces have leaves like this.

Shot one shows the plant from the vantage point of someone looking straight at it, and provides a decent look at its first blooming inflorescence - a single composite flower head.  Shot two looks at the plant from above, so one can see the variability in its leaf shape.

Photographed along the Zinfandel Trail at Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve in Cupertino, CA.

Normally, Picchetti Pond is little more than a dried-out hollow in the earth, with little in it except for a few stray weeds.  WIth all the rain we received in the winter of 2017, however, it filled up beautifully, reaching levels I have never seeen it reach before.  Consequently, it attracted a few Mallards as well as this Canada Goose (Branta canadensis).  I had never seen a Canada Goose at Picchetti before, so this was a first of sorts.

Photographed at Picchetti Pond at Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve, near Cupertino, CA, while the Canada Goose was posing for me.

place_guess: Del Valle Regional Park, Livermore, CA, US

description:
This plant's sprawling, vine-like habit indicates that it is Creeping Snowberry (Symphoricarpos mollis), rather than the other Snowberry in the area, S. albus var. laevigatus, which is a bush.  Its mostly two-flowered inflorescences are another clue that it is S. mollis, as S. ablbus var. laevigatus has inflorescences that generally have 8 or more flowers to them.

This shot is a close-up showing the leaves and flowers (which are not in bloom yet, but definitely thinking about it).  The next shot in this set shows the plant in situ, so it's easy to see its sprawling habit and its lowly stature.  

Photographed along the Zinfandel Trail at Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve, near Cupertino, CA.

Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve is one of the better parks in our area to sea Merriam's Chipmunks going about their business.  I often see them in the trees, keeping an eye out for predators and occassionally uttering their bird-like squeaks. However, this one appeared to be feasting on something (exactly what it was feasting on never became apparent). 

It was so intent on its meal that it ignored me as I photographed it.  I was able to take several shots of it, with this one being the best of the batch.  In this shot, you can see the characteristic pattern of light and dark stripes on its face.

Photographed along the Zinfandel Trail at Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve, near Cupertino, CA.

Weevils found under a rock. They didn't move at all, I offered them to a chicken and she gobbled them up immediately, which means they are familiar fodder. I heard Weevils are what chews up Rhamnus californica leaves sometimes - which we have seen once here in 5 years..
I don't know? The sliver green leaves

description:
Day 1 of one of the greatest vacations ever! Full journal of nature adventures here: http://www.inaturalist.org/journal/sambiology/9891-vacation-in-california-news-flash-i-like-california

Using the great existing observations from the San Francisco Bay area and species guide to help with the ID's -- but please correct me if I've goofed. Almost ALL of these organisms were new for me!

Elizabeth and I stopped at this really amazing preserve in Portola Valley.  Windy Hill Open Space Preserve is a hilly forested area with lots of plant diversity -- trails are nicely maintained too.

Using the great existing observations from the San Francisco Bay area and species guide to help with the ID's -- but please correct me if I've goofed. Almost ALL of these organisms were new for me!

Elizabeth and I stopped at this really amazing preserve in Portola Valley.  Windy Hill Open Space Preserve is a hilly forested area with lots of plant diversity -- trails are nicely maintained too.
place_guess: Windy Hill Open Space Preserve, Portola Valley, California

Using the great existing observations from the San Francisco Bay area and species guide to help with the ID's -- but please correct me if I've goofed.  Almost ALL of these organisms were new for me!

These were from Candlestick Point State Recreational Area -- it was a bit busy with folks today, but we were able to spot some really neat things nonetheless.  Today was a mighty windy day too!
place_guess: Candlestick Point State Recreational Area, San Francisco, California

description:
I found this photogenic grouping of Western Blue-eyed Grass along the Zinfandel Trail at Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve.  This is actually a perplexing wildflower species to shoot, as it opens mainly during sunny weather, but looks really harsh and flat under those conditions.  A passing cloud helped in this case; working quickly, I was able to capture the delicate, almost wispy nature of these wildflowers before the cloud rolled away, causing them to be bathed in harsh sunlight once again.

Accompanying this clump of Western Blue-eyed Grass is some Dove's-Foot Crane's Bill (Erodium molle) and the massive, spiky leaves of some Milk Thistle (Silybum marianum).
